            <h2>Class IV Strong Verbs</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">C</span>lass IV verbs have a (vowel + l/r). For example,
            '<em>beran - to bear</em>' or '<em>stelan - to steal</em>'.  When they conjugate, they follow the vowel change pattern
            <strong>e - æ - ǣ</strong>. So the root vowel in the present is '<strong>e</strong>',
            the root vowel in the past singular (or first past) is '<strong>æ</strong>', and the root vowel in the past plural (or second past) is
            '<strong>ǣ</strong>' (with the macron included here indicating that it is a long vowel). For example, '<em>ic cwele - I die</em>', becomes '<em>ic cwæl - I died</em>' or
                '<em>hie cwǣlon - they died</em>'. Examine the verb '<em>beran - to bear</em>' in the sentences below - 'she carries a spear' and 'she carried a spear'.
            </p>
